WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
Across the world, democracy is on a

00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:06.000
decline. Authoritarianism is on the rise.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Global freedom has eroded for the 18th

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:13.000
consecutive year.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:16.000
Audrey Tang, mm-hmm. What is your

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:18.000
greatest hope for democracy across the globe?

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:24.000
That people see democracy as a

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:26.000
social technology, something that people

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:28.000
can construct together, that they can

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:30.000
improve in the here and now.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:34.000
We can code up political

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:40.000
[Music]

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:42.000
systems. The Sunflower Movement was a

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.000
real turning point for Taiwan's

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:47.000
democracy. When the Sunflower Movement

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:49.000
happened, I typed to my colleague, I have

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:52.000
to leave now. Democracy needs me. I

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.000
brought a very long cable for internet

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:57.000
connection. I live streamed through

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:01.000
Twitter. Everybody saw it is possible for

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:04.000
democracy to evolve, to come up with

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:07.000
novel policies simply by asking the

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.000
people, what should we do?

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.000
[Music]

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:17.000
Together. I was born with a heart defect.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.000
And one day I just fainted. I woke up in

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:23.000
a hospital and they told me the hole in

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:28.000
my heart has grown. I could die. This

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.000
awareness that everything can be reset

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.000
tomorrow reminds me of Taiwanese

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:38.000
democracy. We can lose our democracy

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:40.000
just with a couple of

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:43.000
missiles. I think there's a lot that the

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:46.000
world can learn from

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:50.000
Taiwan. The US is running on a 250-year-old

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:52.000
operating system. There is a strong

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:54.000
desire to move beyond this and

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.000
properly rethink from first principles

00:01:57.000 --> 00:01:59.000
what would democracy in the 21st century

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:01.000
actually look like. We can make the

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:03.000
government more open to the public. It'll

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:05.000
be easier for people to access the data,

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.000
to analyze it.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:09.000
Transparency. Audrey has created the

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:12.000
opportunity to make Taiwan the most

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:14.000
exciting constitutional democracy in the

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
world. I think it's a very critical

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:21.000
moment. China really wants to invade

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Taiwan. You're sitting on a place that is

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:25.000
the flash point if there's going to be

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:29.000
World War III. And yet there's calm in the

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.000
eye of the hurricane. And that calm, I

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.000
think, emanates from all that Audrey's

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:39.000
done. We can become co-creators of our

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:41.000
democratic system, reconfiguring society

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:44.000
in a way that is more transparent, more

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.000
inclusive, more fair.
